-in-genera-ar-768711/| accessdate =2011-02-04 }}</ref>\n| state_delegate3 = Virginia\n| district3 = 16th\n| term_start3 = 2002\n| term_end3 = 2007<ref name=\"FA\"/>\n| preceded3 = Clifton Woodrum\n| succeeded3 = Donald Merricks\n| office4 = Member of [[Chatham, Virginia]] Town Council\n| term_start4 = 2000\n| term_end4 = 2001<ref name=\"FA\"/>\n| preceded4 =\n| succeeded4 =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age | 1969 | 6 | 16}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]]\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse = Kathryn Raine Heithaus\n| children = Charles, Clement, John\n| residence = Chatham, Virginia\n| alma_mater = [[Mississippi College School of Law]], [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] - 1995<br/>[[Hampden-Sydney College]], [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] - 1991\n| profession = [[lawyer|Attorney]]\n| committees = \n| religion = [[Presbyterian]]\n| website = {{URL|hurt.house.gov|Official House website}}<br />{{URL|roberthurtforcongress.com|Campaign website}}\n}}\n\n'''Robert Hurt''' (born June 16, 1969) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|VA|5}}, serving since January 2011. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. The district stretches from [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]] to [[Southside (Virginia)|Southside]] and west to [[Bedford County, Virginia|Bedford]] and [[Franklin County, Virginia|Franklin]] counties. Prior to joining Congress, Hurt was a state senator and delegate, [[City council|councilman]] and attorney.\n\nHurt was born in [[New York City]] and raised in [[Chatham, Virginia]]. After graduating from [[Hampden-Sydney College]] and [[Mississippi College School of Law]], Hurt served as a chief assistant Commonwealth\u2019s Attorney for [[Pittsylvania County, Virginia]] from 1996&nbsp;to 1999. Afterwards, he worked as an attorney for the firm H. Victor Millner, Jr. P.C. in Chatham from 1999&nbsp;to 2008 and opened his own law firm in 2008.\n\nHurt's political career began with his election to the Chatham Town Council. A year later, he was elected to the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] and served three terms. In 2007, Hurt was elected to the [[Senate of Virginia]]. In October 2009, Hurt announced that he would run for the U.S. Representative seat for the 5th congressional district in Virginia. After easily winning the primary, Hurt was elected to the House of Representatives, defeating the incumbent Democrat, [[Tom Perriello]].\n\n==Early life, education, and law career==\nHurt was born in [[New York City]],<ref name=\"FA\">{{cite web| title =Faces of the Senate| publisher =Virginia.gov| year =2010| url =http://hodcap.state.va.us/publications/FaceBook.pdf| accessdate =2010-05-12 }}</ref> where he lived for about nine years.<ref name=\"voters' anxiety\">{{cite web| last =Meola| first =Olympia| title =5th District: Voters' anxiety threatens Perriello| publisher =''Richmond Times-Dispatch''| date =2010-09-05| url =http://www2.timesdispatch.com/news/2010/sep/05/cong05-ar-487631/| accessdate =2010-12-18 }}</ref> His father, Henry Hurt, was a journalist and editor for ''[[Reader's Digest]]''. In 1986, Henry wrote a book questioning the findings of the [[Warren Commission]] called ''Reasonable Doubt: An Investigation into the Assassination of John F. Kennedy''.<ref name=\"NJ\">{{cite web| title =Robert Hurt (R)| publisher =''[[National Journal]]''| date =2010-10-26| url =http://nationaljournal.com/politics/robert-hurt-r--20101026?mrefid=site_search| accessdate =2010-12-22 }}</ref> Hurt was raised in [[Chatham, Virginia]], attended [[Hargrave Military Academy]] and graduated from [[Episcopal High School (Alexandria, Virginia)|Episcopal High School]] in [[Alexandria, Virginia|Alexandria]]. He earned a [[bachelor's degree]] in English from [[Hampden-Sydney College]] in 1991&nbsp;and a [[Juris doctor|law degree]] from [[Mississippi College School of Law]] in 1995.<ref name=\"announces bid\">{{cite web| last =Davis| first =Tim| title =Hurt announces bid for U.S. Congress| publisher =Womack Publishing Service| date =2009-10-07| url =http://www.wpcva.com/articles/2009/10/07/altavista/news/news10.txt| accessdate =2010-05-12 }}</ref> Hurt also graduated from the [[Sorensen Institute for Political Leadership]] program in 2000.<ref name=\"announces bid1\">{{cite web| title =Hurt Announces Bid for U.S. Congress| publisher =[[Sorensen Institute for Political Leadership]]| url =http://www.sorenseninstitute.org/newsroom/asides/hurt-announces-bid-us-congress| date =2009-10-08| accessdate =2011-08-20 }}</ref> He served as a chief assistant Commonwealth\u2019s Attorney for [[Pittsylvania County, Virginia|Pittsylvania County]] from 1996&nbsp;to 1999. From 1999&nbsp;to 2008, Robert worked in a general law practice with the firm of H. Victor Millner, Jr. P.C. in Chatham. In 2008, Robert opened up his own law practice in Chatham.<ref name=\"NJ\"/> Hurt is a member of the [[Kappa Sigma Fraternity]].<ref>{{cite web| last =Huston| first =Andy| title=Greeks in the 113th Congress| publisher =''NIC Blog''| date =2012-12-06| url =http://www.nicindy.org/blog/comments/greeks-in-the-113th-congress/| accessdate =2013-01-03 }}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nHurt began his political career as a member of the Chatham Town Council.<ref name=\"RT\"/> He was elected with 82&nbsp;percent of the vote.<ref name=\"MB\">{{cite web| last =Collins| first =Paul| title =Hurt wins GOP primary| publisher =''Martinsville Bulletin''| date =2010-06-09| url =http://martinsvillebulletin.com/article.cfm?ID=23982| accessdate =2010-06-11 }}</ref> Hurt was first elected to the House of Delegates in 2001&nbsp;and served three terms.<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite web| last =Rucker| first =Janelle| title =Hurt picked to challenge Perriello in 5th District| publisher =''[[The Roanoke Times]]''| date =2010-06-09| url =http://www.roanoke.com/news/roanoke/wb/249730| accessdate =2010-06-11 }}</ref> He represented the 16th District, which includes part of [[Henry County, Virginia|Henry County]]. He was elected and re-elected to the House of Delegates with at least 62&nbsp;percent of the vote.<ref name=\"MB\"/> He cited bringing the New College Institute and the [[Virginia Museum of Natural History]] as accomplishments that he and other legislators of both parties have worked together to bring to the area.<ref name=\"AB\"/>\n\nDuring his time as a delegate, Hurt worked to increase state funding for [[K-12 education]] and increase the safety of Virginia\u2019s children through membership on the Courts of Justice Committee and the Youth Internet Safety Taskforce.<ref name=\"AB\">{{cite web| last =Buck| first =Amanda| title =Hurt bids for seat in Senate| publisher =''Martinsville Bulletin''| date =2007-03-28| url =http://www.martinsvillebulletin.com/article.cfm?ID=8554| accessdate =2011-01-05 }}</ref> Hurt voted two dozen times to cut taxes and supported 28&nbsp;bills in the General Assembly that sought to reduce taxes on food, gas, cigarettes, cars, real estate, computer sales and other items.<ref name=\"opponents say\">{{cite web| last =McNeill| first =Brian| title =Opponents say Hurt\u2019s Web site misleads on voting record| publisher =''[[The Daily Progress]]''| date =2010-01-12| url =http://www2.dailyprogress.com/cdp/news/local/local_govtpolitics/article/opponents_say_hurts_web_site_misleads_on_voting_record/50871/| accessdate =2010-06-18 }}</ref> In 2004, Hurt voted in favor of a $1.4&nbsp;billion tax increase to narrow the gap in Virginia\u2019s budget. Hurt stated that the increase was essential, based on the information lawmakers had at the time, to refrain from a government shutdown over a budget impasse and has since stated regret over the vote.<ref name=\"wants GOP nod\">{{cite web| last =McNeill| first =Brian| title =State senator wants GOP nod for 5th Distric| publisher =''The Daily Progress''| date =2009-10-07| url =http://www2.dailyprogress.com/news/cdp-news-local/2009/oct/07/state_senator_wants_gop_nod_for_5th_district_hurt_-ar-67714/| accessdate =2011-01-05 }}</ref><ref name=\"tax vote\">{{cite web| last =Reed| first =Ray| title =Hurt addresses tax vote in tea party meeting| publisher =''[[The News & Advance]]''| date =2010-08-05| url =http://www2.newsadvance.com/news/2010/aug/05/hurt-addresses-tax-vote-tea-party-meeting-ar-415371/| accessdate =2011-01-09 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, Hurt was elected to the [[Senate of Virginia]], winning 75&nbsp;percent of the vote. Hurt represented the 19th district, which includes the city of [[Danville, Virginia|Danville]], [[Pittsylvania County, Virginia|Pittsylvania]] and [[Franklin County, Virginia|Franklin]] counties, and part of [[Campbell County, Virginia|Campbell]] county.<ref name=\"MB\"/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2010\n{{Main|Virginia's 5th congressional district election, 2010}}\n\n[[Image:Roberthurt.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Hurt speaks at the [[Sorensen Institute for Political Leadership|Sorensen Institute]]]]\n\nOn October 7, 2009, Hurt officially declared himself a candidate for {{ushr|VA|5}}.<ref name=\"aims to\">{{cite web| title =State Sen. Hurt aims to return 5th District to GOP| publisher =''[[The Washington Times]]''| date =2009-10-08| url =http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/oct/08/state-sen-hurt-aims-to-return-5th-district-to-gop/| accessdate =2010-06-18 }}</ref> The district stretches from [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]] to [[Southside (Virginia)|Southside Virginia]] and west to [[Bedford County, Virginia|Bedford]] and [[Franklin County, Virginia|Franklin]] counties.<ref name=\"nomination\">{{cite web| last =Wray| first =Ginny| title =Nomination in hand, Perriello talks strategy| publisher =''[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]''| date =2008-05-19| url =http://www.martinsvillebulletin.com/article.cfm?ID=13896| accessdate =2011-03-04 }}</ref> Hurt was the Republican establishment candidate in the primary and was not received well by the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]].<ref name=\"McKelvey mum\">{{cite web| last =Isenstadt| first =Alex| title =McKelvey mum on Hurt endorsement | publisher =''Politico''| date =2010-06-11| url =http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0610/38412.html| accessdate =2010-06-19 }}</ref> On June 8, 2010, Hurt won the Republican nomination with a plurality in a crowded field of six other candidates.<ref name=\"RT\"/> All of Hurt's opponents in the primary endorsed him.<ref name=\"McKelvey pledges\">{{cite web| title =McKelvey pledges support to Hurt| publisher =''Politico''| date =2010-08-05| url =http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0810/40720.html| accessdate =2010-08-25 }}</ref> A local Tea Party Leader said his group would \"unite behind\" and \"support\" Hurt.<ref name=\"GoDan\">{{cite web| title =Republicans uniting around Hurt to face Perriello| publisher =''Danville Register & Bee''| date =2010-06-09| url =http://www2.godanriver.com/news/2010/jun/09/republicans_uniting_around_hurt_to_face_perriello-ar-268518/| accessdate =2010-08-25 }}</ref>\n\nHurt campaigned against Democratic incumbent [[Tom Perriello]] and Independent candidate Jeffrey Clark in the general election.<ref name=\"Clark to play\">{{cite web| last =McNeill| first =Brian| title =Clark to play role of spoiler in 5th District?| publisher =''The Daily Progress''| date =2010-06-20| url =http://www2.dailyprogress.com/news/cdp-news-local/2010/jun/20/clark_to_play_role_of_spoiler_in_5th_district-ar-319321/| accessdate =2011-01-04 }}</ref> Republicans viewed his as a pickup opportunity and poured resources into the race.<ref name=\"super\">{{cite web| last =Cillizza| first =Chris| title =Super Duper Tuesday Viewer's Guide| publisher =''[[The Washington Post]]''| date =2010-06-08| url =http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/senate/super-duper-tuesday-viewers-gu.html| accessdate =2010-06-12 }}</ref><ref name=\"hopefuls\">{{cite web| last =Sherfinski| first =David| title =Congressional hopefuls assemble war chests ahead of primary| publisher =''[[The Washington Examiner]]''| date =2010-06-06| url =http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/local/Congressional-hopefuls-assemble-war-chests-ahead-of-primary-95660699.html| accessdate =2010-06-12 }}{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref> Perriello was listed as one of the 10&nbsp;most vulnerable House incumbents by ''[[Roll Call]]''.<ref name=\"poll portrays\">{{cite web| title =Virginia: GOP Poll Portrays Hurt as Unquestioned Frontrunner| publisher =[[Congressional Quarterly]]| date =2010-05-18| url =http://blogs.cqpolitics.com/eyeon2010/2010/05/virginia-gop-poll-portrays-hur.html| accessdate =2010-06-12 }}{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref> Hurt was a member of the [[National Republican Congressional Committee]]'s \"Young Guns\" program.<ref name=\"young gun\">{{cite web| title =NRCC Adds 16 To 'Young Gun' Ranks| publisher =Congressional Quarterly| date =2010-06-30| url =http://blogs.cqpolitics.com/eyeon2010/2010/06/nrcc-young-gun.html| accessdate =2010-07-08 }}{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn June 12, Hurt stated that he would \"absolutely\" participate in debates that included all the candidates, including Independent candidate Clark. Just days later, Hurt stated that he would not debate Clark. Although the statement was made in response to a direct query from a reporter as to whether he would debate Clark, Hurt\u2019s campaign later tried to justify their position by insisting this was untrue.<ref name=\"3-way debate\">{{cite web| last =McNeill| first =Brian| title =Hurt, Perriello differ on 3-way debate| publisher =''The Daily Progress''| date =2010-06-18| url =http://www2.dailyprogress.com/cdp/news/local/local_govtpolitics/article/hurt_perriello_differ_on_3-way_debate/57390/| accessdate =2010-06-20 }}</ref> Hurt skipped the first debate which was organized by the Senior Statesmen of Virginia, becoming the first candidate to skip the forum since it started in 1996.<ref name=\"skip debate\">{{cite web| last =McNeill| first =Brian| title =Hurt to skip debate with Perriello, Clark| publisher =''The Daily Progress''| date =2010-08-11| url =http://www2.dailyprogress.com/news/2010/aug/11/hurt-skip-debate-perriello-clark-ar-421053/| accessdate =2010-08-22 }}</ref><ref name=\"opponents criticize\">{{cite web| last =McNeill| first =Brian| title =Opponents criticize Hurt for skipping 5th District debate| publisher =''The Daily Progress''| date =2010-08-12| url =http://www2.dailyprogress.com/news/cdp-news/2010/aug/11/2/opponents-criticize-hurt-skipping-5th-district-deb-ar-422896/| accessdate =2011-01-05}}</ref> In addition to the first debate, Hurt skipped two subsequent debates one sponsored by the [[Chamber of Commerce]] in [[Nelson County, Virginia|Nelson County]] and another hosted by [[American Legion]] Post 325 in Danville making a total of three skipped debates.<ref name=\"without Hurt\">{{cite web| last =Lewis| first =Dannika| title =Perriello, Clark debate without Hurt| publisher =[[WVIR-TV]]| date =2010-10-10| url =http://www.nbc29.com/story/13180241/hurt-skips-another-5th-district-debate| accessdate =2010-10-15}}</ref><ref name=\"gentleman's debate\">{{cite web|last=McGrath|first=Erin|title=Perriello, Clark meet in 'gentleman's debate'|url=http://www2.nelsoncountytimes.com/news/nelson-news/2010/sep/15/perriello-clark-meet-gentlemans-debate-ar-506632/|accessdate=2011-03-23|publisher=''Nelson County Times''|date=2010-09-15|author2=Ray Reed}}</ref>\n\nHurt campaigned on his opposition to the Democratic-backed initiatives that Perriello supported, such as [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|health-care reform]], the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act|economic stimulus package]] and [[American Clean Energy and Security Act|clean energy legislation]].<ref name=\"unseats Perriello\">{{cite web| last =McNeill| first =Brian| title =Hurt unseats Perriello| publisher =''The Daily Progress''| date =2010-10-02| url =http://www2.dailyprogress.com/news/2010/nov/02/hurt-unseats-perriello-ar-625511/| accessdate =2011-01-05}}</ref> On August 20, Hurt released his first television ad. Hurt's first television ad stated that he would fight tax increases, stop Washington\u2019s spending and start creating jobs, however he never mentions his opponent. \"You definitely see that he\u2019s running against Congress as a whole and Democrats as a whole,\" Isaac Wood, an analyst at the [[University of Virginia Center for Politics]], said. \"That was very clear. He spent just a few seconds introducing himself, then pivoted right away to attack the negative things happening in D.C. With voters, that can be effective.\"<ref name=\"taking shape\">{{cite web| last =Amos| first =Catherine| title =5th District campaigns taking shape| publisher =''Danville Register & Bee''| date =2010-08-21| url =http://www2.godanriver.com/news/2010/aug/21/5th-district-campaigns-taking-shape-ar-465932/| accessdate =2010-08-25 }}</ref> Another ad from Hurt called Perriello a \"rubber stamp\" for the policies of President [[Barack Obama]] and House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]].<ref name=\"rubber stamp\">{{cite web| last =Pershing| first =Ben| title =Hurt ad calls Perriello a 'rubber stamp' for Obama, Pelosi| publisher =''The Washington Post''| date =2010-10-15| url =http://voices.washingtonpost.com/virginiapolitics/2010/10/hurt_ad_calls_perriello_a_rubb.html| accessdate =2010-10-16 }}</ref> Hurt won with 51&nbsp;percent of the vote.<ref name=\"race wrap-up\">{{cite web| title =Virginia congressional race wrap-up| publisher =[[WTOP-FM]]| url =http://www.wtopnews.com/?nid=25&sid=2103221| accessdate =2011-01-05 }}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Virginia, 2012#District 5}}\nHurt was challenged by Democratic nominee [[John W. Douglass|John Douglass]], a retired United States Air Force Brigadier General and former Assistant Secretary of the Navy. Hurt won re-election to a second term on November 6, 2012.\n\n===Tenure===\nAfter his win, Hurt submitted a formal letter of resignation from the [[Virginia General Assembly]] to Governor [[Bob McDonnell]] that would be effective on January 5, the day Hurt was sworn into Congress.<ref name=\"formally resign\">{{cite web| last =Helderman| first =Rosalind S.| title =Hurt, Griffith formally resign from General Assembly to join Congress| publisher =''The Washington Post''| date =2010-11-22| url =http://voices.washingtonpost.com/virginiapolitics/2010/11/hurt_griffith_formally_resign.html| accessdate =2011-01-09 }}</ref> Hurt voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] which successfully passed the House.<ref name=hcrrepeal>{{cite web|last=Hatcher|first=Angela|title=Rep. Robert Hurt hopeful Senate will also pass health care repeal|url=http://www2.wsls.com/news/2011/jan/19/robert-hurt-hopeful-senate-will-also-pass-health-c-ar-785573/|accessdate=2011-03-24|publisher=[[WSLS-TV]]|date=2011-01-19}}</ref> In February, Hurt criticized President [[Barack Obama]]'s $3.73&nbsp;trillion 2012&nbsp;federal budget proposal for its excessive spending and borrowing.<ref name=\"bashes Obama's\">{{cite web| title =Rep. Robert Hurt bashes Obama's budget proposal| publisher =WSLS-TV| date =2011-02-14| url =http://www2.wsls.com/news/2011/feb/14/rep-robert-hurt-bashes-obamas-budget-proposal-ar-842361/| accessdate =2011-03-04 }}</ref> Hurt would vote to pass a $1.2&nbsp;trillion bill that would cut the year's budget federal budget by $61&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"needs to stop\">{{cite web| last =Hatcher| first =Angela| title =Rep. Robert Hurt: Senate needs to stop government shutdown| publisher =WSLS-TV| date =2011-02-22| url =http://www2.wsls.com/news/2011/feb/22/congressman-robert-hurt-senate-needs-stop-governme-ar-860274/| accessdate =2011-03-04 }}\n*{{cite web| author =Associated Press| title =House passes more than $60B in spending cuts| publisher =[[CBS News]]| date =2011-02-19| url =http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/02/19/politics/main20033828.shtml| accessdate =2011-03-04 }}{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref> On April 8, Hurt voted for a continuing resolution that prevented the government from shutting down that day.<ref name=\"fund bill\">{{cite web| title =Griffith, Hurt OK fund bill | publisher =''Martinsville Bulletin''| date =2011-04-10| url =http://www.martinsvillebulletin.com/article.cfm?ID=28066| accessdate =2011-04-11 }}</ref> Hurt expressed support for [[Paul Ryan]]'s [[The Path to Prosperity|budget plan]] that month as well.<ref>{{cite web| last =Reed| first =Ray| title =Hurt says he supports Ryan budget plan| publisher =WSLS-TV| date =2011-04-28| url =http://www2.wsls.com/news/2011/apr/28/hurt-says-he-supports-ryan-budget-plan-ar-1003958/| accessdate =2012-02-11 }}</ref> On July 19, Hurt voted for the [[Cut, Cap and Balance Act]].<ref name=\"budget cut bill\">{{cite web|last=Holland|first=Tiffany|title=Hurt votes for budget cut bill|url=http://www2.newsadvance.com/news/2011/jul/20/hurt-votes-budget-cut-bill-ar-1186106/|publisher=''The News & Advance''|accessdate=2011-07-28|date=2011-07-20}}</ref> On August 1, Hurt voted for the [[Budget Control Act of 2011]] that raised the debt ceiling and cut spending by $2.1&nbsp;trillion over the next 10&nbsp;years.<ref name=\"right direction\">{{cite web|last=Holland|first=Tiffany|title=Hurt: Debt bill step in right direction|url=http://www2.wsls.com/news/2011/aug/03/hurt-debt-bill-step-right-direction-ar-1216538/|publisher=WSLS-TV|accessdate=2011-08-04|date=2011-08-03}}</ref> Hurt co-sponsored a bill that would prevent the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] from cracking down on farm dust. The bill passed the House on December 8.<ref>{{cite web|title=House passes bill to prevent EPA from regulating farm dust|url=http://www2.newsadvance.com/news/2011/dec/08/house-passes-bill-prevent-epa-regulating-farm-dust-ar-1531079/|publisher=''The News & Advance''|accessdate=2011-12-14|date=2011-12-08}}</ref>\n\n;Social issues\nVirginia Citizens Defense League, a pro-gun organization, gave Hurt an 78% approval rating. Asked if he supports the purchase and possession of guns, Hurt has consistently affirmed his support for gun rights.<ref name=\"votesmart courage\">[http://www.votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/50895/robert-hurt/ Project Vote Smart<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nHurt has traditionally voted for legislation that restricts abortion. Virginia Society for Human Rights gave him a 100% approval rating.<ref name=\"votesmart evaluations\">[http://www.votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/50895/robert-hurt Robert Hurt Ratings and Endorsements - Project Vote Smart<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Planned Parenthood and NARAL Pro-Choice have consistently given him 0% approval ratings every year since 2002.<ref name=\"votesmart evaluations\"/>\n\nEquality Virginia has given him between 0% and 11% approval ratings for his position on LGBT rights.<ref name=\"votesmart evaluations\"/>\n\nHurt has affirmed that he supports [[capital punishment]] for certain crimes.<ref name=\"votesmart courage\"/>\n\n;Fiscal issues\nHurt cosponsored the [[Balanced Budget Amendment]], which did not pass the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] in November 2011. Hurt said of the bill, \u201cBy passing a Balanced Budget Amendment, Congress will be required to spend no more than it takes in, reining in out of control spending once and for all\u201d<ref name=\"house press release\">[http://hurt.house.gov/press-release/roberts-round-we-need-constitutional-amendment-balance-our-budget Robert's Round-Up: We Need A Constitutional Amendment To Balance Our Budget | Congressman Robert Hurt<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Hurt also sponsored the Small Business Capital Access and Job Preservation Act that would exempt private equity funds advisers from certain registration and reporting standards.<ref name=\"govtrack\">[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h112-1082&tab=summary H.R. 1082 - Summary: Small Business Capital Access and Job Preservation Act (GovTrack.us)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In July, 2011 Hurt sponsored the Market Transparency and Taxpayer Protection Act which would \u201cprotect the taxpayers of the United States by requiring Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac to sell or dispose of the assets of such enterprises that are not critical to their missions.\u201d <ref name=\"govtrack1\">[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/billtext.xpd?bill=h112-2440 Read The Bill: H.R. 2440 - GovTrack.us<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> However, because very little political leverage was used to pass this legislation, it most likely will die in committee.<ref name=\"govtrack1\"/> Hurt\u2019s position on Government regulation is clear in his statement that \u201cBy reducing the unnecessary government regulations that hinder small businesses, keeping taxes low and allowing people to keep more of what they make, and cutting spending to get our fiscal house in order, the private sector will gain the confidence necessary to expand and create the jobs that the people of the 5th District need and deserve.\u201d <ref name=\"govtrack2\">[http://hurt.house.gov/issue/economy Economy and Jobs | Congressman Robert Hurt<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nDuring 2000-2010, the Virginia League of Conservation Voters gave Hurt an average approval rating of 40%.<ref name=\"votesmart evaluations\"/> However, in 2010, when Hurt was running against incumbent Tom Perriello, the [[Sierra Club]] and [[League of Conservation Voters]] released television and radio ads against Hurt, attacking him on an alleged conflict of interest regarding uranium mining. However, the ads were deemed to be false by independent fact checkers due to the fact Robert Hurt had no personal investment in uranium mining.<ref name=\"Fact Check\">[http://www.politifact.com/virginia/statements/2010/oct/31/sierra-club/conservation-groups-accuse-robert-hurt-conflict-in/]</ref> Hurt strongly opposed House Speaker Nancy Pelosi\u2019s 2009 proposed \u201cCap-and Trade\u201d climate control legislation.<ref name=\"climate\">[http://thehill.com/blogs/e2-wire/e2-wire/126515-hurt-highlights-perriello-climate-vote-ahead-of-obama-visit Hurt highlights Perriello climate vote ahead of Obama visit - The Hill's E2-Wire<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Hurt called on the Virginia Department of Interior secretary Ken Salazar to remove bans on off-shore drilling and development.<ref name=\"offshore energy\">[http://hurt.house.gov/press-release/virginia-members-call-interior-department-reconsider-commonwealth-offshore-energy Virginia Members Call On Interior Department To Reconsider Commonwealth Offshore Energy Development Ban | Congressman Robert Hurt<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nHurt has made it a priority to rein in federal over-regulation on the private sector. Hurt cosponsored the Farm Dust Prevention Regulation Act,<ref name=\"H.R. 1633\">[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr1633 - Summary: Farm Dust Regulation Prevention Act (GovTrack.us)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> the Preserving Rural Resources Act,<ref name=\"H.R. 4278\">[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr4278 - Summary: Preserving Rural Resources Act (GovTrack.us)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and the Supporting Home Owner Rights Enforcement Act.<ref name=\"H.R. 3663\">[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr3663 - Summary: Supporting Home Owner Rights Enforcement Act (GovTrack.us)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He has voted to ensure that cost-benefit analysis is applied to federal rulemaking in order to ensure that regulation will not have a negative impact on the economy or destroy jobs, and he has voted to roll back currently proposed regulations that would put many in the energy industry out of business. Hurt has been a staunch opponent to the Affordable Care Act, of which he says, \u201cThe President\u2019s health care law represents a fundamental departure from the founding principles of our nation by placing more faith in government than in the American people and by inserting the federal government in between patients and their doctors.\u201d <ref name=\" What they're saying about the healthcare ruling\">[http://www2.newsadvance.com/news/2012/jun/28/what-theyre-saying-about-healthcare-ruling-ar-2021667/ - Summary: What they're saying about the healthcare ruling (Lynchburg News & Advance)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n====Bills sponsored====\nThe following is an incomplete list of major bills sponsored by Rep. Hurt.\n* [[Audit Integrity and Job Protection Act (H.R. 1564; 113th Congress)]] ({{USBill|113|H.R.|1564}}) - The bill would \"amend the [[Sarbanes-Oxley Act|Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002]] (SOX) to deny the [[Public Company Accounting Oversight Board]] any authority to require that [[Financial audit|audits]] conducted for a particular issuer of securities in accordance with SOX standards be conducted by specific auditors, or that such audits be conducted for an issuer by different auditors on a rotating basis,\" according to a summary by the [[Congressional Research Service]].<ref name=1564sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 1564 - Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/1564|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=11 July 2013}}</ref>  The bill passed the House 321-62 on July 8, 2013.\n*[[Small Business Capital Access and Job Preservation Act (H.R. 1105; 113th Congress)]] - The bill would exempt investment advisers from the [[Security and Exchange Commission]]\u2019s (SEC\u2019s) registration and reporting requirements when they provide advice to a [[private equity fund]] with outstanding debt that is less than twice the amount of capital that has been committed to and invested by the fund.<ref name=cbo1105>{{cite web|title=CBO - H.R. 1105|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/44409|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref> On December 4, 2013, the House voted in [http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2013/roll622.xml Roll Call Vote 622] to pass the bill 254-159.<ref name=1105allactions>{{cite web|title=H.R. 1105 - All Actions|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/1105/all-actions/|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises|Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises]]\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Insurance, Housing and Community Opportunity|Subcommittee on Insurance, Housing and Community Opportunity]] (Vice Chair)\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ Virginia House of Delegates, District 16: Results 2001 to 2005<ref name=\"vpap\">{{cite web| title =Robert Hurt - Elections History| publisher =Virginia Public Access Project| url =http://www.vpap.org/candidates/profile/elections/24590| accessdate =2011-02-04 }}</ref>\n!Year\n!\n!Republican\n!Votes\n!Pct\n!\n!Democrat\n!Votes\n!Pct\n!\n!Third Party\n!Party\n!Votes\n!Pct\n|-\n|2001\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |{{nowrap|'''Robert Hurt'''}}\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |11,853\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |65%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Randy Collins\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |6,382\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |35%\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |{{nowrap|'''Robert Hurt'''}}\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |8,744\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |62%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |{{nowrap|Kimble Reynolds, Jr.}}\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |5,441\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |38%\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |{{nowrap|'''Robert Hurt'''}}\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |12,821